                                    <p>Lead tablet with a single fold. It preserves one inscription on side A (<ref target="i-dodone-online-15a">15A</ref>) and three on side B (<ref target="i-dodone-online-16b">16B</ref>, 17B, and 18B). Inscriptions <ref target="i-dodone-online-15a">15A</ref> and <ref target="i-dodone-online-16b">16B</ref> were written by the same hand: <ref target="i-dodone-online-15a">15A</ref> records Thelytos’ question, whereas <ref target="i-dodone-online-16b">16B</ref> gives only his name. Evangelidis edited 17B together with <ref target="i-dodone-online-16b">16B</ref>, and <bibl><ptr target="#CIOD"/></bibl> likewise includes both texts under the same lemma. As the editors of <bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneDVC"/></bibl> point out, however, 17B and 18B are independent inscriptions, with 17B incised over 18B, which is therefore earlier. Inscription 18B was not identified by Evangelidis.</p>
                                    <p n="Dialect"><rs type="dialect" ref="#Thessalian">Thessalian (Histiaeotis)</rs>.</p>
                                    <p n="Alphabet"><rs type="alphabet" ref="#Archaic">Archaic, red (Ψ for X)</rs>.</p>
