                <p><bibl><ptr target="#Evangelidis1952"/>, <citedRange>302</citedRange></bibl> (<bibl><ptr target="#BE"/> <citedRange>1956, 143.8</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/> <citedRange>15.388</citedRange></bibl>); <bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneLhôte"/> <citedRange>36</citedRange></bibl> (<bibl><ptr target="#MéndezDosuna2008"/>, <citedRange>72</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#NietoIzquierdo2017"/>, <citedRange>113</citedRange></bibl>); <bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneDVC"/> <citedRange>17B</citedRange></bibl> (<bibl><ptr target="#MéndezDosuna2018b"/>, <citedRange>287</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#Johnston2021"/>, <citedRange>111, 112</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#CIOD"/> <citedRange>15A+16B+17B</citedRange></bibl> [last consulted 10/07/2026]).</p>
                </div>
<div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc">
    <ab>
        <lb n="1"/>αἰ κα μὰ ἔχ; 
    </ab>
</div>
            <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
     <p>If I do not have?</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="es">
        <p>¿Si no tengo?</p>
        </div>
            <div type="commentary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
<p>According to Lhôte (<bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneLhôte"/></bibl>), this is a summary of Thelytos’ enquiry written by the personnel of the sanctuary in the local alphabet of Dodona. This hypothesis was rightly questioned by  <bibl><ptr target="#Johnston2021"/></bibl>, who, in turn, identified the text as the oracle’s response, although without further explanation (for the vexed question of the responses on the oracular tablets, see <bibl><ptr target="#MartínGonzález2021"/></bibl>). The different dialect, alphabet, letter forms, and phraseology used in this text, however, indicate that it is an independent enquiry, as argued by the editors of <bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneDVC"/></bibl>. If their reading is correct, the text consists of a concise question whose object remains unexpressed. The consultation takes the form of a conditional sentence introduced by αἰ (for this formulation in the oracular tablets, see <bibl><ptr target="#NietoIzquierdo2017"/></bibl>). On the negative <foreign xml:lang="grc">μά</foreign> for <foreign xml:lang="grc">μή</foreign>, see <bibl><ptr target="#MéndezDosuna2018b"/>, <citedRange>287</citedRange>.</bibl></p>
                 
                <p n="Ithaca results">Delphi ranks first with a probability of 29.54%, followed by Epirus in second place (14.86%). Chronologically, the highest probability (4.87%) is assigned to the 450-440 BC interval, although the model distributes comparable probabilities across a broad range of dates. See <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline17B_2026_06_24.html">Ithaca results</ref> and <ref target="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/IDodone/IDodoneOnline/refs/heads/main/ithaca-results/IDodoneOnline17B.md">metadata</ref>, and a snapshot of the <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline17B_geographical-attribution_2026_06.jpg">geographical attribution</ref>.</p>
                </div>
        </body>
